    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-02-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-02-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="9"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d9">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/6419</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_PWH1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Page</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 5722</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-02-13">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 13, 1918</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The Department has received your telegram No.
                    7459 of October 17, 1917, and your despatch No. 6762 of August 13, 1917, with
                    which you transmitted a copy of a note dated August 10, 1917, from the British
                    Foreign Office, together with copies of <hi rend="italic">British Treaty
                        Series</hi>, Nos. 2 and 4 of 1914; No. 5 of 1915 and No. 6 of 1917, enclosed
                    therewith, concerning the convention of November 9, 1914, and the subsequent
                    extensions thereof, concluded between Great Britain and France and acceded to by
                    Italy and Russia, to regulate captures made by the naval forces of the
                    respective countries in the present war,<note n="1" xml:id="d9fn1">Not
                        printed.</note> and inquiring whether the Government of the United States is
                    disposed to accede thereto.</p>
                <p>The Department has carefully considered the enclosures transmitted with your
                    despatch and desires you to inform the British Foreign Office that the
                    Government of the United States, in view of the present character of the war,
                    deems it advisable to defer consideration of the question of the accession of
                    the United States to these conventions and agreements.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
